Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Trim the @carrot{2} then slice into thin rounds. Pop the carrots onto a #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and scatter over the @ground cumin{1}.

Toss to coat then spread out in a single layer. Roast until soft and golden, ~{15-16%minutes}, turning halfway through.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{240} for the couscous and half the @chicken stock powder{1} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, remove from the heat, stir in the @couscous{120} and pop a lid on the pan. Leave to the side for ~{8-10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. When the pan is hot, add the @lamb mince{200} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces). Roughly chop the @prunes{40}(roughly chopped). Roughly chop the @dill{1}(stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated, or use a garlic press).

Lower the heat of the lamb pan to medium and add the onion. Cook until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the garlic, @tomato puree{30} and @harissa paste{50}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @water{100} for the lamb to the lamb mixture, along with the remaining stock powder and the prunes. Stir together and bring to a gentle simmer. Cook until the mixture is thick and saucy, ~{5-7%minutes}, adding a splash of water if the sauce is a little thick. Season to taste with salt and pepper if needed.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, mix the @low fat natural yoghurt{75} with half the dill. Season with salt and pepper. Carefully fluff up the couscous with a #fork{}, stir through the remaining dill and season with salt and pepper.

Divide the couscous between bowls and spoon over the lamb mixture. Top with the roasted carrots and spoon over the dill yoghurt. Enjoy!